'''Kazama clan''' (風間氏) is one of the {{ill|Clans in Japan|ja|日本の氏族}}. According to legend, it originated in {{ill|979 AD|ja|979年}} during the {{ill|Tengen era|ja|天元 (日本)}} when a branch of the {{ill|Suwa clan|ja|諏訪氏}}, dispatched to serve at {{ill|Kazama Shrine|ja|風間神社}} in {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国}} {{ill|Minochi District|ja|水内郡}}, adopted the surname Kazama. The clan is considered one of the {{ill|Jinke-to|ja|神家党}}, a lineage of Shinto priest families.

== Niigata Prefecture ==
The Kazama clan became prominent as {{ill|Local lords|ja|土豪}} in {{ill|Echigo Province|ja|越後国}}.
* They are said to trace their roots to {{ill|Kazama Shrine|ja|風間神社}} in {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国}}. According to legend, {{ill|Kazama Tachibano|ja|風間橘五}} settled there while serving under {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshinaka|ja|源義仲}}, also known as Kiso Yoshinaka.{{Sfn|Ōta|1934|p=1457}}
* During the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代}}, Kazama Nobuaki, a {{ill|South Court (Japan)|ja|南朝 (日本)}} commander and Shinano Governor, fought valiantly under {{ill|Nitta Yoshisada|ja|新田義貞}}, inflicting significant damage on the {{ill|North Court (Japan)|ja|北朝 (日本)}} and {{ill|Ashikaga Takauji|ja|足利尊氏}}. He is said to have been a disciple of {{ill|Nichishō|ja|日昭}}, one of the {{ill|Six Elder Priests of Nichiren|ja|六老僧}}, and founded temples like {{ill|Hama Tsuchihokkeji|ja|浜土法華寺}} and {{ill|Murata Myōhōji|ja|妙法寺 (長岡市)}}.

=== Murakami ===
The Murakami branch of the Kazama clan originated in {{ill|Niitsu, Sawakami|ja|新津沢海}} but later moved to {{ill|Murakami Domain|ja|村上藩}}, where they became prominent as textile merchants.

== Yamagata Prefecture ==
=== Sakata ===
In {{ill|1725 (Kyōhō 10)|ja|享保10年}}, the third head of the Murakami Kazama family, {{ill|Kazama Hikosō|ja|風間彦惣}}, moved to {{ill|Sakata|ja|酒田市}}, marking the establishment of the Sakata Kazama lineage.

